<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,310,1569,1595]" box="[189,310,1569,1595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1569,1595]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1569,1595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[187,1399,1618,1758]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1912" box="[189,268,1618,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Baliga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,268,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Baliga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1911" box="[476,627,1619,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Hagenomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[476,627,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Hagenomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[683,818,1618,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Myrmeleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[683,818,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Myrmeleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1911" box="[1169,1320,1619,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Hagenomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1169,1320,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Hagenomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the female anterior gonocoxites 8 relatively shorter than posterior gonocoxites 8 (these 
<specimenCount box="[1177,1309,1656,1683]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="female">two female</specimenCount>
genital sclerites are nearly equal length in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1911" box="[589,740,1694,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Hagenomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[589,740,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Hagenomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[867,1002,1694,1720]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Myrmeleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[867,1002,1694,1720]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Myrmeleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of interconnected crossveins in the costal area of forewing (these interconnected crossveins are absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[1211,1346,1731,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Myrmeleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1211,1346,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Myrmeleon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,342,1799,1825]" box="[189,342,1799,1825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,1799,1825]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1799,1825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[187,1401,1848,2025]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1912" box="[189,268,1848,1874]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Baliga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,268,1848,1874]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Baliga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
currently includes 17 described species, predominantly distributed in the Oriental (12 species) and Palaearctic regions (4 spp.: 
<collectingCountry box="[556,629,1885,1911]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[639,709,1886,1912]" name="Japan" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Japan</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[766,840,1886,1912]" name="South Korea" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Korea</collectingCountry>
) with a single species in 
<collectingCountry box="[1122,1230,1885,1911]" name="Australia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1243,1389,1885,1911]" country="Australia" name="Queensland" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Queensland</collectingRegion>
). It is widely distributed in the Oriental region: 
<collectingCountry box="[724,864,1923,1949]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[875,948,1923,1949]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[960,1023,1923,1949]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1034,1150,1924,1950]" name="Myanmar" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1162,1279,1923,1949]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1290,1392,1923,1949]" name="Vietnam" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, and the main islands of 
<collectingCountry box="[474,591,1961,1987]" name="Indonesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[604,715,1961,1987]" name="Malaysia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[727,862,1961,1987]" name="Micronesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Micronesia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[875,1010,1961,1987]" name="Philippines" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1023,1093,1961,1987]" name="Japan" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Japan</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1156,1228,1961,1987]" name="South Korea" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ghosh S. K." box="[1247,1391,1961,1987]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 179" refId="ref16269" refString="Ghosh S. K. 2000. Neuroptera fauna of North-East India. Records of the Zoological Survey of India, Occasional Paper: 184, i - xiii + 1 - 179." type="journal article" year="2000">Ghosh 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Stange L. A." box="[189,335,1998,2024]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 565" refId="ref19159" refString="Stange L. A. 2004. A systematic catalog, bibliography and classification of the world antlions (Insecta: Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae). Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 74: 1 - 565." type="journal article" year="2004">Stange 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bao R. &amp; Shen Z. R. &amp; Wang X. L." box="[350,531,1998,2025]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="45 - 48" refId="ref15783" refString="Bao R., Shen Z. R. &amp; Wang X. L. 2007. A review of the species of Hagenomyia from China (Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (N. S.) 43: 45 - 48. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00379271.2007.10697492" type="journal article" year="2007">
Bao 
<emphasis box="[405,464,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayashi H. &amp; Matsumoto R. &amp; Sugawara H. &amp; Liu X. Y." box="[546,775,1998,2024]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="235 - 251" refId="ref16573" refString="Hayashi H., Matsumoto R., Sugawara H. &amp; Liu X. Y. 2020. Two new species of Baliga (Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae: Myrmeleontinae) with the molecular phylogeny of the tribe Myrmeleontini in Japan. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology 26 (2): 235 - 251." type="journal article" year="2020">
Hayashi 
<emphasis box="[649,709,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
